Rules of Engagement: Level 1
Time Limit: 60 Minutes.

The Environment: A fresh, running RHEL 9 VM. You are logged in as a regular user who has sudo privileges (or just log in as root).

The Goal: Accuracy over speed.

📝 RHCSA Mock Exam: Beginner Level ("Bootcamp")
Task 1: System Reconnaissance

Find your system's current hostname and write it into a new file located at /root/system_info.txt.

Task 2: The Directory Tree

Create a nested directory structure in one command: /opt/training/linux101.

Inside linux101, create an empty file named practice.txt.

Task 3: Basic User Management

Create a new user named intern1.

Set their password to linuxisfun.

Task 4: Group Assignment

Create a new group named juniors.

Add the user intern1 to the juniors group.

Task 5: Ownership and Permissions

Change the group ownership of the directory /opt/training/linux101 to the juniors group.

Change the permissions on /opt/training/linux101 so that the Owner and Group have Read, Write, and Execute (rwx) access, but Others have zero access (---).

Task 6: Text Manipulation

Add the sentence "I am learning Red Hat" to the file /opt/training/linux101/practice.txt. (Do this from the command line, do not open a text editor like vim or nano).

Task 7: Searching for Text (Grep)

Search the file /etc/services for the exact word ssh.

Save only the lines that match into a new file at /root/ssh_port.txt.

Task 8: Archiving and Compression (Tar)

Create a gzip-compressed archive of the entire /opt/training directory.

Save the archive as /root/training_backup.tar.gz.

Task 9: Package Management

Using the command line, install the package tmux.

(Note: Your VM needs internet access to reach the default Red Hat or CentOS Stream repositories).

Task 10: Basic Service Management

The SSH service is critical. Verify its current status.

Ensure the service named sshd is enabled to start automatically every time the server boots.
